metadata.name: Contort #123
metadata.description:
Contort is the result of combining several previously meaningless experiments and learnings into a single cohesive algorithm. The project comes in a variety of shapes, bends, twists, colors, and other variations.  

The artwork builds towards the end-result by rendering a fixed number of forms per frame to ensure a smooth rendering process. Rendering times can vary depending on which features are combined by the hash.

metadata.name: Modern Times #274
metadata.description:
Created by Eko33, a generative artist featured at the Tezos Ecosystem Exhibition (Art Basel Miami 2021).

This generative artwork creates a limited series of distinctive artworks based on unique hash seeds.

The algorithmic approach of this collection generates a broad spectrum of unique outcomes, inspired by the "giant machine" from the movie "Modern Times."

Beyond a classic mechanical representation, Eko33 aims to convey multiple emotions while embracing the cold nature of algorithms.

Computer-generated generative art can be seen as a gigantic assembly line. Still, its true nature gives the artist complete freedom from all commercially available tools/constraints.

The collection "Modern Times" highlights the dark ages of generative arts using a bichromatic color palette and evolves toward the contemporary "Digital Renaissance" era using warmer, more acid and "pop" colors.

About Eko33:
Official fx(hash) page: https://www.fxhash.xyz/u/Eko33
Official Website: https://www.eko33.com/

metadata.name: Gestalt #1050
metadata.description:
"Gestalt" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at The Ever-Evolving World of Art, Art Basel Hong-Kong, 2022

A flurry of many elements derived from my past (and future) strewn across a single canvas. As random as things seem, collectively time tends to reveal hints of order in the chaos. Sometimes, more is more.

Controls:
• Left-click/tap reassembles the piece with one less element each time
• 'R' reassembles the piece with all elements
• 'S' saves the output

“𝚃𝚑𝚎 𝚠𝚑𝚘𝚕𝚎 𝚒𝚜 𝚐𝚛𝚎𝚊𝚝𝚎𝚛 𝚝𝚑𝚊𝚗 𝚝𝚑𝚎 𝚜𝚞𝚖 𝚘𝚏 𝚒𝚝𝚜 𝚙𝚊𝚛𝚝𝚜.”

Made in p5js
Created May 2022
Artist: @Yazid

metadata.name: Scaffold #192
metadata.description:
The thoughts we have are rarely as ordered as the words we speak and the actions we take are shaped by expectation and conditioning.

As we grow up, we are taught to behave or even think in a certain way. We learn what is acceptable and what is not. Our thoughts are forced to align with the structure imposed upon us.

Scaffold is an attempt to visually explore this concept of thoughts and control. Each output represents a state of mind at a particular moment in time.

Palettes have been mostly named by my family based on the first word they thought of when they saw them.

Keyboard commands:

s - save as png
h - toggle high resolution 
b - toggle background texture
a - switch aspect ratio
r - new moment

metadata.name: a necessary reaction #53
metadata.description:
This piece has an interesting (to me) history. I originally started by trying to clone my IRL physical painting style in Midjourney. I got very close, then I had the idea to make a generative piece that could recreate the Midjourney recreation of my physical paintings. 

As is the nature of things, this result has departed quite a bit from my original intentions. You can scroll through the last two weeks of my Twitter feed to follow the entire process and see the original source. During the course of this writing process, crypto crashed, and the piece got darker and darker. 

There are certain combinations which will result on a matte black on matte black image (that I've taken to calling "carbon mode." A mint is in carbon mode when both palettes are 1, with a gesture on top. This is definitely the darkest mint I've done for FxHash, or even in general, and matches my mood as I watch my net worth drill to the core of the Earth. I am, however, an optimist, and I fully expect to look back on this month and laugh. Hopefully in the not-too-distant future.

metadata.name: Interlaced #157
metadata.description:
From African tribal clothes to Islamic mosaics every civilization throughout history has produced delicate patterns to share the essence of their culture. These artifacts have changed our understanding of how art, like societies form through bonds, the very fabric of things that have become symbols for cycles, paths and relationships.

Interlaced explores these unique motifs using emergent algorithms to produce colorful continuous patterns. The project uses a dynamic engine that traverses triangular meshes placing diverse tile configurations. By combining art with technology, the project aims to tell a new story of making digital connections between geography, culture and time.

Press “s” to save in high-resolution.

metadata.name: L-2D CA #189
metadata.description:
Audiovisual architecture of a two dimensional cellular automation. An initial randomisation process is followed by a layering ritual. Time = space: cell states are locked into their corresponding positions on the elevation axis.

Touch to listen.
